  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address money laundering at both the national and international levels. Below are some key examples:\n\n### United States\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**  \n   - Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering by maintaining records and reporting suspicious activities.\n\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**  \n   - Criminalizes money laundering and establishes it as a federal offense. It also requires financial institutions to report cash transactions over $10,000.\n\n3. **Patriot Act of 2001**  \n   - Strengthens anti-money laundering (AML) laws by enhancing due diligence requirements, improving information sharing between financial institutions and law enforcement, and expanding penalties for AML violations.\n\n4. **USA PATRIOT Act**  \n   - Contains provisions to combat money laundering, including requirements for financial institutions to establish AML programs and report suspicious activities.\n\n### International\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**  \n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets global standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats. Its recommendations are adopted by many countries.\n\n2. **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**  \n   - One of the first international treaties to address money laundering, focusing on drug-related proceeds.\n\n3. **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**  \n   - Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions to combat money laundering linked to organized crime.\n\n4. **European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**  \n   - A series of directives that harmonize AML regulations across EU member states, requiring enhanced due diligence, transparency, and reporting.\n\n### Other Notable Laws and Frameworks\n- **Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA) in the UK**  \n- **Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorism Financing Act in Australia**  \n- **Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)** in various countries, which collect and analyze financial data to combat money laundering.\n\nThese laws and frameworks are continuously updated to address evolving methods of money laundering and to ensure global cooperation in combating financial crimes.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
